---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<ProjectLayout
  title="Predicting Bus Trip Performance with Machine Learning"
  year="2025"
  section="Data Science & Analysis"
  category="Bar-Ilan University · Data Science Programme"
  tools={['Python', 'XGBoost', 'SMOTE', 'Optuna', 'SHAP', 'scikit-learn']}
>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Background</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Bus reliability is one of the biggest factors shaping whether people choose public transport —
        yet operators often only learn a line is unreliable after the fact. Built as part of
        <strong>Bar-Ilan University's Data Science programme</strong> with <strong>Tamir Edelstein</strong>
        of <strong>Elia Transportation Engineering Ltd.</strong>, this project set out to predict —
        before or during a trip — whether a bus would arrive <em>early</em>, <em>on time</em>, or
        <em>delayed</em>, giving operators a tool for proactive scheduling and dispatching decisions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Methodology</h2>
    <ul class="proj-list">
      <li>Merged real-time vehicle positions and trip records from the <strong>SIRI API</strong> with <strong>GTFS</strong> timetables, passenger counts, weather data and route-network GIS layers into a single trip-level dataset.</li>
      <li>Engineered temporal, spatial, operational and historical-probability features capturing how each line and segment had performed before.</li>
      <li>Trained and compared <strong>Logistic Regression</strong>, <strong>Random Forest</strong>, <strong>LightGBM</strong> and <strong>XGBoost</strong> as a three-class classifier, addressing class imbalance with <strong>SMOTE</strong> and tuning the final model with <strong>Optuna</strong>.</li>
      <li>Used <strong>SHAP</strong> values to explain predictions feature-by-feature, rather than treating the model as a black box.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Results</h2>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/ml-bus-delay-roc-curves.jpg`}
      alt="ROC curves comparing Logistic Regression, Random Forest, XGBoost and LightGBM across the early, delay and on-time classes"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      ROC curves across all three classes: XGBoost (red) and LightGBM (orange) clearly outperform the simpler
      baselines, reaching AUC scores of 0.83 (early), 0.90 (delay) and 0.90 (on-time).
    </p>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/ml-bus-delay-shap-summary.png`}
      alt="SHAP summary plot showing which features most influence the model's prediction of a delayed trip"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      SHAP summary for the "delay" class — line/direction identity, the historical probability of running early
      by hour, and arrival hour emerge as the strongest drivers of a delay prediction.
    </p>
    <ul class="proj-list">
      <li>The selected <strong>XGBoost</strong> classifier reached roughly <strong>83% accuracy</strong> — well above the ~74% "always predict the most common class" baseline — and performed especially strongly on the operationally critical delay class (precision 0.86, recall 0.94).</li>
      <li><strong>SHAP</strong> analysis showed that line identity, historical on-time probability by hour, and time of day were the strongest predictors of delay.</li>
      <li>Distinguishing "early" from "on-time" trips remained the hardest part of the problem — both are rare and easy to confuse, a limitation the project documents as a direction for further work.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Code</h2>
    <p class="proj-body">
      The full notebooks, data pipeline and write-up are available on GitHub.
    </p>
    <a class="proj-external" href="https://github.com/ofer-geo/public_transport_ML" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
      View repository on GitHub →
    </a>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>

<style>
  :global(.proj-list) {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 10px;
    max-width: 68ch;
  }
  :global(.proj-list li) {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: #2A2A2A;
    padding-left: 1.2em;
    position: relative;
  }
  :global(.proj-list li::before) {
    content: '—';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: #3D5E35;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .proj-external {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-top: 12px;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #3D5E35;
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .proj-external:hover { text-decoration: underline; }
</style>
